1. Fitting Linear Model to Penguin Data: Predicting Body Weight of a Penguin Based on Their Other Features

lm Models and Summary Plots

  • Fitting linear models using lm()

  • Generating summary plots to visualize the fits

  • Let’s try to predict the body weight of a penguin based on its other features.

  • We can first look at how the different features are related using the pairs plot.

#names(penguins)
pairs( select(penguins, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, flipper_length_mm, body_mass_g) )

  • Flipper length seems to be most clearly related to body mass so we can build a linear model based on that. In R we use the lm function to construct linear regression models (using the method of least squares).
# input X : flipper length
# output Y : body mass
model1 <- lm(body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm, data=penguins )
plot(body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm, data=penguins)
abline(model1) # y = a + bx

summary(model1)

Call:
lm(formula = body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm, data = penguins)

  • Resulting formula : body_mass_g = -5780 + flipper_length_mm*49.686

  • We can look at the diagnostic plots for the fit using the following command.

plot(model1)

Examining residual and measuring performance

  • The line of best fit is chosen to minimise the sum of the squared residuals.
  • If we want to manually work with the residuals we can access them with the following command:
# we can access the individual components of the fitted model
# using $
# e.g. access vector of residuals
# model1$residuals
# to plot the residuals
hist(model1$residuals)

Recall

RSS is a measure of the discrepancy between the observed values of the target variable \(y\) and the values predicted by the model \(ŷ\). Mathematically, RSS is calculated as the sum of the squared differences between the observed values of \(y\) and the predicted values of \(ŷ\):

\[ \text{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 \]

  • Here,
  • \(y_i\) represents the observed value of the target variable for the i-th data point, and
  • \(\hat{y}_i\) represents the predicted value of the target variable for the \(i^{th}\) data point.

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)

  • RMSE is a measure of the average magnitude of the residuals (the differences between predicted and actual values) of the model.
  • It is calculated by taking the square root of the average of squared differences between predicted and actual values:

\[ \text{RMSE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2} \]

RMSE gives a measure of how well the model predicts the target variable. - A lower RMSE indicates a better fit of the model to the data.

R-squared (Coefficient of Determination)

R-squared is a statistical measure that represents the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable \(y\) that is predictable from the independent variables (features) in the model. - It ranges from \(0\) to \(1\), where \(0\) indicates that the model explains none of the variability of the response data around its mean, and \(1\) indicates that the model explains all the variability. - R-squared is calculated as:

\[ R^2 = 1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}} \]

where TSS (Total Sum of Squares) is the sum of the squared differences between the observed \(y\) values and the mean of \(y\).

  • can quantify the quality of different fits using a number of related measures:
  • RSS residual sum of squares
  • MSE mean squared error \(MSE =\frac{RSS}{N}\)
  • RMSE root mean squared error \(RMSE =\sqrt{MSE}\)
  • We can calculate these in R using:
# measures of fit performance
# RSS sum of squared residuals
res <- model1$residuals
RSS <- sum(res^2)
RSS
[1] 52854796
n <- nrow(penguins)
# MSE mean squared error
MSE <- RSS/n
MSE
[1] 153647.7
# RMSE root mean squared error
RMSE <- sqrt(MSE)
RMSE
[1] 391.9792
  • Note that the measure of fit shown in the summary is the R squared value. We can access this from the fit using code like:
summary(model1)$r.squared
[1] 0.7589925

Transforming variables

  • In some cases we see that we can transform a relationship to a linear form by taking the logarithm of the data. Typical transformations are plotting \(\log(y)\) against \(x\) (when the underlying relationship is \(y = a \times bx\)) or plotting \(\log(y)\) against \(\log(x)\) when the underlying relationship is \(y = a \times xb\)).

  • We can do this using code like the following:

model3 <- lm(body_mass_g ~ log(flipper_length_mm), data=penguins )
plot(body_mass_g ~ log(flipper_length_mm), data=penguins)
abline(model3)

screenreg(list(model1,model2,model3))

  • In this case fitting body mass against log(flipper length) did not improve the fit (which might be expected as there is no visual evidence that the relationship between the two follows a non-linear power law relationship).
  • Another way to work with log transformed values is to add columns to the dataset e.g.
penguins <- penguins %>%
mutate( log_flipper_length_mm = log(flipper_length_mm),
log_body_mass_g = log(body_mass_g) )

Multivariate Fitting Variables

  • So far the fits we have looked at include only one predictor. However it is easy in R to make a linear model that includes several predictors:
# sometimes taking the log of a variable can transform
# the relationship with the output to a linear relation
model4 <- lm(body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm + bill_length_mm + bill_depth_mm + species
, data=penguins )
summary(model4)

Call:
lm(formula = body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm + bill_length_mm + 
    bill_depth_mm + species, data = penguins)

Residuals:

  • We see that adding in all variables including species makes a significant improvement to our model performance (R squared value has increased to 0.85). This might be expected because we know different species have different body shapes.
  • In this case the final formula for predicting body mass from the set of inputs is:
#body_mass_g= -4327.327 + 20.241* flipper_length_mm
#                        + 41.468*bill_length_mm
#                       +140.328*bill_depth_mm
#                       -513.247*speciesChinstrap 
#                       + 934.887*speciesGentoo

  • Note that because species is a category variable, R adds in dummy variables speciesChinstrap and speciesGentoo.

  • speciesChinstrap is a variable that has value 1 for entries of species Chinstrap, and 0 otherwise.

  • speciesGentoo is a variable that has value 1 for entries of species Gentoo, and 0 otherwise.

  • Effectively the coefficients of these variables encode the average difference in mass between the baseline category of species Adelie, i.e.

    • the average Chinstrap penguin weighs 513g less than the average Adelie penguin

    • the average Gentoo penguin weighs 935g more than the average Adelie penguin

Extra notes: Converting Numeric Values to Category values

  • In some cases it is useful to segment our dataset into groups based on a numerical value.

  • We can do this with the cut function.

  • This takes a series of breaks to bin the data, and optionally labels that can be used to label the resulting groups.

  • As an example lets view the distribution of penguin weights and split them into categories of small medium and large penguins.

hist(penguins$body_mass_g)

  • convert weight to small (<3000g) medium (3000 to 5000g) and large (>5000g)
# the cut function can convert a numeric to factor variable
penguins <- penguins %>% mutate( size = cut(body_mass_g,
breaks=c(0,3000,5000,10000),
labels=c("small","medium","large")))
summary(penguins$size)
 small medium  large   NA's 
    11    270     61      2
  • If we want more groups it can be useful to use the seq function to generate the breaks.
  • We can also use cut_number, cut_interval, cut_width from the tidyverse that can help choose automated groupings (google tidyverse cut to see how these can be used).
# the cut function can uses seq to generate a series of cut points
penguins <- penguins %>% mutate( size = cut(body_mass_g,
breaks= seq(2000,8000,500) ))
table(penguins$size)

2. Multivariate Linear Regression Models Using Real Estate Dataset

Dataset Description

  • To begin with, download and open the datafile: real_estate.csv. This dataset stores data on house prices (normalized to per unit area, e.g., price per square meter).
  • The columns in this dataset are:

    • sale_date: Year and date (decimal) corresponding to the sale date.

    • house_age: Age of the house in years.

    • dist_to_transport: Distance to the nearest train station.

    • num_stores: Number of stores close by (within a certain radius) of the property.

    • longitude: Longitudinal coordinate of the property.

    • latitude: Latitude coordinate of the property.

    • price_per_sqm: Price of the property per square meter.

Exercise 1

  • Load in the data file.

  • Check that the data types are set up appropriately.

  • Check the amount of data in the dataset, and whether there is any missing data.

  • Think: What relationships might you expect to find in this dataset?

  • Explore the relationships between the variables and the price.

  • Identify which factors seem to be most important in determining house price.

  • Determine if there are any factors that do not seem important.

  • Investigate other relationships between the input variables.

  • Once you have explored the data, try to make plots that illustrate your key findings.

Objectives

We want to use this dataset to:

  1. Understand the factors that make some houses more expensive than others.
  2. Build a statistical model to predict an appropriate house price for a property.

Let us start by loading the real_estate dataset.

Stepwise Model Selection

  • Using stepwise regression for model selection

  • Evaluating the models selected by stepwise regression

  • Stepwise model selection builds up our model step-by-step.

  • This can be done using the StepAIC function from the MASS package.

# install.package("MASS")
library(tidyverse)
library(MASS)

Attaching package: 'MASS'
The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':

    select
# to ensure that we use select from the tidyverse dplyr package
select <- dplyr::select
  • Template code for running stepwise selection.
  • Run using the following configuration gives forward selection starting with an empty model and adding variables one by one. To start we try running a single step (add a single variable):
# make a model which predicts price with no input variables
# effectively predicts using the mean
model_min <- lm(price_per_sqm ~ 1, data=real_estate )

# we can define the largest possible model using 
# a dot . to mean include everything
model_max <- lm(price_per_sqm ~ . -dist_to_transport, data=real_estate )

scp <- list(lower = model_min, upper = model_max)
model_step <- stepAIC(model_min,
                      direction = "forward",
                      scope = scp,
                      steps = 1)

Exhaustive Search for Variable Selection

  • Instead of stepping to add or remove variables to a model, we can also exhaustively try every combination of possible input variables and see which gives the best performance.

  • The following code shows hwo to use the leaps package to do this:

# install.packages("leaps")
library(leaps)
Warning: package 'leaps' was built under R version 4.2.3
regsubsets_out <- regsubsets( price_per_sqm ~ . - dist_to_transport,
                             data = real_estate,
                             nbest = 1,
                             nvmax = NULL,
                             force.in = NULL,
                             force.out = NULL,
                             method = 'exhaustive'
                            )
summary(regsubsets_out)

plot(regsubsets_out, scale='adjr2', main='Adjusted Rsq')

  • In this case this analysis found the best performing model to be the one with all 6 predictors, followed by the model with all predictors except longitude.

  • We can view the exact adjusted R-squared values for each model using the following code:

summary(regsubsets_out)$adjr
[1] 0.5704569 0.6302911 0.6641489 0.6821354 0.6890538 0.6892051
# identify which has best i.e. max adjusted Rsq entry in this set:
which.max(summary(regsubsets_out)$adjr)
[1] 6
  • We see model 6 has best fit (just!) measured by Adjusted R-squared.
  • We can also see how they perform by alternative fit measure BIC:
summary(regsubsets_out)$bic
[1] -337.9555 -394.8906 -429.5435 -447.2636 -451.3420 -446.5355
# identify which has best i.e. min BIC entry in this set:
which.min(summary(regsubsets_out)$bic)
[1] 5
  • In this case model 5 is suggested to be best by this measure. However in practice if we look at the difference in values there is only a small difference in performance between model 5 and 6, if the difference was larger we might expect consistent results whether we compare adjusted R squared or BIC measures of fit.

      1. A model with a single numerical predictor.
      2. A model with two numerical predictors.
      3. A model with one numerical and one categorical predictor.
      4. A model with all predictors included.
  4. Optimize the Model:
    • Try to find an optimized model using stepwise or exhaustive search methods.
